tweet:

- Indoor shopping malls must close.

tweet: Our Workforce Solutions Department has gone after wage theft, standing up for workers against bad actors who are violating the law and taking advantage of them. #StateOfTheStateNM

tweet: Why is this legislation important? Because New Mexico has the eighth highest rate of gun deaths in the United States, with a suicide rate at least 50% higher than the national average and over 50% of suicides caused by a firearm. #SB5 #nmleg2020

name: Michelle Lujan Grisham
tweet:

#SB5 #nmleg2020

name: Michelle Lujan Grisham
tweet: Extreme-risk protection orders are proactive, bipartisan, and proven effective, allowing police and family to temporarily take firearms and ammunition from someone threatening themselves or others. #SB5 #nmleg2020

name: Michelle Lujan Grisham
tweet:
This budget makes bold investments in education, economic development, public safety, and the care and wellbeing of New Mexicans, continuing to build the brighter future that all New Mexico families deserve.

See the full budget here:  http://bit.ly/37FNFbt

name: Michelle Lujan Grisham
tweet: 👮‍♀️ Underscoring a commitment to protecting New Mexico families with $163.9 million for public safety, including funding for 60 new State Police officers and a new data-sharing system to address gaps in inter-agency communication around the state

name: Michelle Lujan Grisham
tweet: 👴 $25 million to create the Kiki Saavedra Senior Dignity Fund, addressing high-priority areas for seniors across New Mexico including transportation, food insecurity, physical and behavioral health services, case management, and caregiver services

name: Michelle Lujan Grisham
tweet: 🧠 A $28.7 million increase to build a new behavioral health network, including community-based health services, effectively addressing substance use disorders, and addressing the behavioral needs of individuals in the justice system

name: Michelle Lujan Grisham
tweet: 💊 Funding to create a new Office of Wholesale Drug Importation within NMDOH to develop, plan, apply for & negotiate w/ the federal government for approval of a Canadian wholesale drug importation plan, working directly to reduce the costs of prescription drugs for New Mexicans

name: Michelle Lujan Grisham
tweet: 🩺 Major investments in caring for New Mexicans’ health and wellbeing, including funding to serve additional New Mexicans on the Developmentally Disabled waiver waiting list and develop a new supports waiver service, as well as a $58 million increase to the Medicaid budget

name: Michelle Lujan Grisham
tweet: 📈 A continuation of critical investments in economic development and successes in diversifying & expanding the economy, including $200 million for roads, bridges and rail projects, $40 million for LEDA, $9 million for job training, and funds to grow outdoor rec, film, & tourism

name: Michelle Lujan Grisham
tweet: 👨‍🎓 $35 million to fund the New Mexico Opportunity Scholarship to make college tuition-free for New Mexico residents, restoring the initial promise of the Lottery Scholarship and re-establishing essential career pathways for New Mexicans across the state

name: Michelle Lujan Grisham
tweet: 👩‍🏫 A $200.3 million increase in the public schools budget, including the most significant back-to-back raises for educators in over a decade and increases in whole-child education, bilingual and multicultural frameworks, community schools, and STEAM education

name: Michelle Lujan Grisham
tweet: 👫 $320 million to create the new Early Childhood Trust Fund, providing a dedicated and self-sustaining revenue stream to fund early childhood programs into the future

name: Michelle Lujan Grisham
tweet: 👶 A $74 million increase in early childhood services to establish a fully functioning Early Childhood Education and Care Department, including expanding child care assistance, raises for child care providers, more slots for pre-k, and expanded home visiting services

name: Michelle Lujan Grisham
tweet: 🎓 An expansion of the education moonshot to cover education from cradle to career, with more than 47% of all new recurring spending going toward education, from early childhood to higher ed
